{
  "local_port": 53768,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are examples of prefixes and suffixes?",
  "response": "Prefixes and suffixes are types of affixes, which are word parts added to a root word to modify its meaning. Here are some examples:\n\n### Prefixes\nPrefixes are added to the beginning of a root word. Here are some common prefixes:\n\n1. **un-** (not)  \n   - Example: unhappy (not happy)\n  \n2. **re-** (again)  \n   - Example: redo (do again)\n  \n3. **pre-** (before)  \n   - Example: prehistoric (before recorded history)\n  \n4. **dis-** (not, or opposite of)  \n   - Example: disagree (not agree)\n  \n5. **sub-** (under, below)  \n   - Example: submarine (underwater)\n  \n6. **mis-** (wrongly)  \n   - Example: misunderstand (understand wrongly)\n\n7. **inter-** (between, among)  \n   - Example: international (between nations)\n\n8. **semi-** (half, partly)  \n   - Example: semicircle (half a circle)\n\n### Suffixes\nSuffixes are added to the end of a root word. Here are some common suffixes:\n\n1. **-ing** (action or process)  \n   - Example: running (the action of running)\n  \n2. **-ed** (past tense)  \n   - Example: walked (past tense of walk)\n  \n3. **-ly** (in a certain manner)  \n   - Example: quickly (in a quick manner)\n  \n4. **-ness** (state or quality)  \n   - Example: happiness (state of being happy)\n  \n5. **-ful** (full of)  \n   - Example: joyful (full of joy)\n  \n6. **-less** (without)  \n   - Example: helpless (without help)\n\n7. **-er/-or** (one who does)  \n   - Example: teacher (one who teaches)\n\n8. **-ity** (state or condition)  \n   - Example: activity (state of being active)\n\nThese prefixes and suffixes can combine with various root words to create new meanings and parts of speech.",
